content: Welcome to Online Renju Class lesson.
Today we will review and analyse some games that were played in the Tampere Open tournament last weekend.
And even the strong Latvian player Arnis Veidemanis made come-back to renju, with successful games.
Before he retired, he was about 7 dan player.
The tournament was played with RIF rules.
This was my first game, I was black.
Lauri Toivonen from Finland was white.
This 8th move is not very often played.
I believe most of you know it. So lets discuss it a bit.
Where do you think is a good 9th move?
you suggested mostly j8 and g11.
soujun now can NOT make moves on board
this 10th move seems to take care of the f8 attack
maybe b can attack at upper area
Samsone, benben, Andry, slappanu, Ikon, out, soujun, Yue, jinzhiyuye, yuelee00, Shangjin, slamduk, madrock, shuwang, xuwu, Asuka.
but your hand is so efficiant
seems no good way to attack from here
not so good anymore for black maybe
what should white do? any ideas?
ok, i will follow your advice
g8 is the same as g10 ?
furthermore, 24 on right side was not necessary
white could defend from g6 at once
but it requires lots of knowledge.
If you play without any knowledge,
then this 9th here is the safest way.
then you can use this 9th here.
In the tournament last week, I did not have much knowledge about 9-g11.
I am not even sure, whether it is black or white advantage.
But I know at least 9-j8 and 9-g8 give black confident advantage immediately,
without needing to struggle in defense.
I wanted to practise the straight style, so I went 9-g8.
this move is new to me.
perhaps there are other ways too
As you know, if white defends from the bottom,
just your own memory, not library or software
i put a main branch here quickly,
then we can analyse the upper 10th
f6 and f7 are the only points
vcf takes more moves than threat
this is the vct for this 10th move.
Then the tactics for black is to play here.
Is this variant familiar for you? Has anyone of you played it before?
compared to standard i11 opening variant, the stone at g8 is different from stanfard f8 stone.
the stone at g8 stands better than in f8,
because white cannot control the line g9_g8_g7 actively,
while they could control it in case of f8_g7 line.
If white tries to be active now,
black wins. do you see it?
for active playing, white has to control the h11 point as well as f8 point.
so let me put some other stone,
and let you attack as black.
who wants to be black here
therefore 14-g6 may be one of the strongest moves for white.
This also happened in our game.
suppose, white would play the most aggressive move - h5.
White is forced to play more passive move.
the students without vct solvers usually say "me" fast :)
its most exciting to say "me" even when you are not sure how it ends
just as a challenge of oneself
About using the solvers - remember one good thing:
here in renjuclass we don't care about "right answers",
but about how we can develop our own brain and skills
so, whoever uses any solver, is just stopping his own progress
what do you suggest for 17th move?
its obvious that white then goes j6, so what is your next move then?
your plan was to go f11,
usually, we play a three or four only when necessary.
if the idea was to go f11, we check -
if we skip j9, can white take j9
if white cannot self take j9, then black's j9 move is a waste
it means, if white cannot go j9 next,
then black can always go j9 anytime later.
the more you can postpone your three or four,
the more attack potential you gain
obviously, white has a bad position now
so, if your true idea was to take f11, then its best to go there directly.
who will be black, say me
In my game, i was more careful
It seemed safe, and yet very powerful.
Now, white has a tough challenge.
it would remove the j5 forbidden point,
which means, black can take j5,
and gets a huge advantage below
also, black can control the key points e8 and f5, if necessary
black should not go g11 now,
because white would just stop from h11,
and the outcome is worse for black.
trying to provoke white to go f9, and give me j5 point.
White has made the best moves so far, in my opinion.
Does black have straight win now?
may be it is hard for me.
because i know many people use vct solvers. and if solver fails to find win, the student will be afraid to say "me"
I don't know,, I didn't find any
to early,, I take back one
can't find the win,, but I'm sure there is
In the game, i searched for straight win for a long time,
but since I did not find,
during the whole time, whote cannot touch the line 12_14.
This was the key of black power -
not to waste any three to stop 12_14,
since white self cannot touch 12_14 anyway.
and by keeping black lines open,
black can use different ways of attack later.
including just playing to f9 in some case, if necessary
And there is no better 26 either.
In the of of today's lesson,
lets come back to this 26th move.
(there were vcf when I gave up)
So, as I see it, the moves from 9 to 25 were quite forced,
and gave black a strong advantage.
Which means, those who like safe style,
all you need to learn is those few counter attack variants from move 12
Now, in my tournament experience, I have used j8 (about 3-4 times),
Maybe next time, I will try g11. :))
The lesson will end now, thank you all.
